## Exercise 3

##### Write a MPI program with two processes in such a way that the process 0 sends a message (array of float) containing 1000 random reals to process 1.

##### Investigate how back-and-forth message passing time varies with the size of the message.

<img src="pw5.assets/image-20211106224146450.png" alt="image-20211106224146450" style="zoom:80%;" />

| # elements | Time     |
| ---------- | -------- |
| 100        | 0.000059 |
| 1000       | 0.000152 |
| 10000      | 0.000250 |
| 1e5        | 0.000356 |
| 1e6        | 0.003048 |
| 1e7        | 0.032755 |
| 1e8        | 0.264147 |

As we can see from the obtained data, with the small number of elements the increase is approximately linear, however with the number of elements more than 100,000 we can start to notice an exponential increase in communication time. 

![img](data:image/png;base64,)

![img](data:image/png;base64,)

##### Complete the program in such a way that processes 0 and 1 perform 9 Ping-Pong, while varying the message size, and measure the communication duration each time. 

<img src="pw5.assets/image-20211106232751677.png" alt="image-20211106232751677" style="zoom: 80%;" />

| # elements | Time     |
| ---------- | -------- |
| 100        | 0.000034 |
| 1000       | 0.000075 |
| 10000      | 0.000176 |
| 1e5        | 0.000788 |
| 1e6        | 0.008027 |
| 1e7        | 0.121606 |
| 1e8        | 1.236214 |

As a result, we can see more steep exponential change in a 9 time exchange, with the expected proportional delay relative to the 1 time exchange. Both experiments prove that there is a limit in throughput and latency on the local machine memory, the signs in higher delay start to occur with more than 100,000 exchanged elements.
